<p>
  Title case is a capitalization style where the principal words in a title or heading are written with an initial capital letter. It's the standard format for book titles, article headlines, movie names, and formal documents. But the rules have nuances — not every word gets capitalized, and different style guides disagree on the finer points.
</p>
<p>
  This guide covers exactly which words to capitalize, explains the differences between the major style guides, and shows you how to convert any text to title case instantly.
</p>

<h2>Title Case Rules: The Core Principle</h2>

<p>
  The fundamental rule of title case is: <strong>capitalize all "principal" words and lowercase the minor words</strong> (unless they appear at the start or end of the title).
</p>

<p><strong>Always capitalize:</strong></p>
<ul>
  <li>The first and last word of the title (regardless of what they are)</li>
  <li>Nouns: <em>river, teacher, city, idea</em></li>
  <li>Pronouns: <em>I, he, she, it, we, they</em></li>
  <li>Verbs: <em>run, be, think, write</em></li>
  <li>Adjectives: <em>free, long, beautiful, first</em></li>
  <li>Adverbs: <em>quickly, never, always</em></li>
  <li>Subordinating conjunctions: <em>although, because, since, while, if, when</em></li>
</ul>

<p><strong>Usually lowercase:</strong></p>
<ul>
  <li>Articles: <em>a, an, the</em></li>
  <li>Short prepositions (under 5 letters): <em>at, by, for, in, of, on, to, up</em></li>
  <li>Coordinating conjunctions: <em>and, but, or, nor, for, so, yet</em></li>
</ul>

<h2>Title Case Examples</h2>

<p>Here's how the rules apply in practice:</p>

<ul>
  <li>✅ <strong>The Art of Public Speaking</strong> ("of" is lowercased)</li>
  <li>✅ <strong>A Guide to Writing for the Web</strong> ("A" capitalized as first word, "to" and "for" and "the" lowercased)</li>
  <li>✅ <strong>How to Start and Run a Successful Blog</strong> ("to", "and", "a" lowercased)</li>
  <li>✅ <strong>Up in the Air</strong> ("Up" capitalized as first word, "in" and "the" lowercased)</li>
  <li>✅ <strong>Running for Office Is Hard</strong> ("for" lowercased, "Is" capitalized as a verb)</li>
</ul>

