<h2>Title Case vs Sentence Case</h2>

<p>
  These two styles are the most common choices for web content and headings:
</p>

<p>
  <strong>Title Case:</strong> The First Letter of Most Words Is Capitalized<br />
  <strong>Sentence case:</strong> Only the first word and proper nouns are capitalized
</p>

<p>
  Modern web writing and content marketing have largely shifted to sentence case for headings because it feels less formal and more readable at a glance. Publications like The Guardian, Medium, and most tech blogs use sentence case for article headings.
</p>

<p>
  Book titles, movie names, album names, and formal document titles traditionally use title case.
</p>

<h2>Style Guide Differences</h2>

<p>
  Different style guides have slightly different rules for edge cases:
</p>

<h3>APA (American Psychological Association)</h3>
<p>Capitalize words of 4 letters or more. Lowercase: <em>a, an, the, and, but, for, or, nor, at, by, in, of, on, to, up</em>.</p>

<h3>Chicago Manual of Style</h3>
<p>One of the most detailed guides. Capitalizes all words except articles, prepositions of any length, and coordinating conjunctions — unless they appear first or last.</p>

<h3>AP Style (Associated Press)</h3>
<p>Used by most news outlets. Capitalizes all words of 4 letters or more, including longer prepositions like "from," "with," and "into."</p>

<h3>MLA (Modern Language Association)</h3>
<p>Similar to Chicago: capitalize all words except articles, short prepositions, and coordinating conjunctions.</p>

<h2>When to Use Title Case</h2>

<ul>
  <li><strong>Book, film, song, and album titles</strong> — always title case</li>
  <li><strong>Formal report headings</strong> — title case adds authority</li>
  <li><strong>Website navigation items</strong> — short labels benefit from title case</li>
  <li><strong>Email subject lines</strong> — some brands use title case for a professional appearance</li>
  <li><strong>Product names and features</strong> — e.g., "Premium Plan", "Advanced Analytics"</li>
</ul>

